1 Pre-processing data

df <- read.table("claim_history.csv", header = TRUE, sep = ",")
# Create the Frequency variable by dividing the CLM_COUNT by EXPOSURE
df$Frequency <- df$CLM_COUNT / df$EXPOSURE
# Create a binary target variable Event that determines if the Frequency is strictly greater than one 
df$Event <- ifelse(df$Frequency > 1, 1, 0)
# Use MSTATUS, CAR_TYPE, REVOKED, and URBANICITY as the categorical predictors
# Use CAR_AGE, MVR_PTS, TIF, and TRAVTIME as the interval predictors
# Drop all missing values (i.e., NaN) of all the predictors and the target variable before training your model

After I test out my method on CAR_AGE and verified my logic, I am looping through all the 8 predictors to print out the plots.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# Assuming df_focus is your dataframe and Event is your binary target variable

# Convert categorical columns to factors
categorical_columns <- c('MSTATUS', 'CAR_TYPE', 'REVOKED', 'URBANICITY')
df_focus[categorical_columns] <- lapply(df_focus[categorical_columns], as.factor)

predictors <- c('MSTATUS', 'CAR_TYPE', 'REVOKED', 'URBANICITY', 'CAR_AGE', 'MVR_PTS', 'TIF', 'TRAVTIME')

# Loop through each predictor
for (predictor in predictors) {
  
  # Create a summary dataframe with odds of Event by predictor's unique values
  summary_data <- df_focus %>%
    group_by(!!sym(predictor)) %>%
    summarize(Odds = (sum(Event == 1) / n()) / (1 - sum(Event == 1) / n())) # u/(1-u)
  
  colnames(summary_data) <- c('predictor', 'Odds') 
  
  # Convert predictor to numeric for the x-axis
  summary_data$predictor_numeric <- as.numeric(as.factor(summary_data$predictor))
  
  # Sort the summary dataframe by predictor's unique values in ascending order
  summary_data <- summary_data[order(summary_data$predictor_numeric), ]
  
  # Print the summary data
  # print(head(summary_data))
  
  # Create line chart
  g <- ggplot(summary_data, aes(x = predictor_numeric, y = Odds)) +
    geom_line() +
    labs(title = paste("Odds of Event by", predictor),
         x = predictor,
         y = "Odds") +
    theme_minimal()
  
  print(g)
}

# null.model is only with the intercept
null.model <- glm(Event ~ 1, data=subset(df_focus_factor, select = -c(Frequency, EXPOSURE)), family="binomial")
# full.model has all the 8 predictors
full.model <- glm(Event ~ ., data=subset(df_focus_factor, select = -c(Frequency, EXPOSURE)), family="binomial")

# If the predicted Event probability of an observation is greater than or equal to 0.25, then you will classify that observation as the Event (i.e., filing more than one claim per unit exposure).  An observation is correctly classified if the predicted target value equals the observed target value.  The Accuracy metric is the proportion of observations that are correctly classified.

df_focus_factor$Predicted_Event <- ifelse(df_focus_factor$predicted_event_probability >= 0.25, 1, 0)
# df_focus_factor
nrow(subset(df_focus_factor, Predicted_Event == Event))
## [1] 6525
nrow(df_focus_factor)
## [1] 9662
cat("Model accuracy:\n")
## Model accuracy:
nrow(subset(df_focus_factor, Predicted_Event == Event)) / nrow(df_focus_factor)
## [1] 0.675326
cat("The model correctly classifies 67.5% of observations.")
## The model correctly classifies 67.5% of observations.
write.csv(df_focus_factor, file = "df_focus_factor.csv")

y_test  <- y[-inTrain]
